  "prompt": "Why do cold days seem slightly warmer when it rains?",
  "response": "Cold days can seem slightly warmer when it rains due to a combination of physical and psychological factors:\n\n### 1. **Increased Humidity:**\n   - Rain increases the relative humidity in the air. Humid air feels slightly warmer than dry air at the same temperature because it conducts heat more efficiently and reduces the cooling effect of evaporation on your skin.\n\n### 2. **Reduced Wind Chill:**\n   - Rain often coincides with calmer wind conditions. Wind can make cold air feel much colder by stripping away the thin layer of warmth that surrounds your body (wind chill effect). Without wind, the air feels less biting.\n\n### 3. **Thermal Inertia:**\n   - Rainwater often retains some warmth from the surrounding environment, especially if the ground or air is not freezing. This can slightly elevate the perceived temperature.\n\n### 4. **Psychological Factors:**\n   - Rain can create a cozy, insulated feeling, especially if you\u2019re indoors or wearing appropriate clothing. This sense of comfort can make the cold seem less intense.\n\n### 5. **Cloud Cover:**\n   - Rain is typically associated with cloud cover, which traps some of the Earth\u2019s heat. On a clear cold day, heat escapes more easily into the atmosphere, making it feel colder.\n\nThat said, if the temperature is near or below freezing, rain can actually make it feel much colder due to the risk of freezing rain or sleet, which can be dangerous and uncomfortable. But in milder cold conditions, rain can create a damp warmth that feels less harsh than dry, windy cold.",
